metadata.name: StairWaves #125
metadata.description:
StairWaves is a generative collection imagining abstract stairs built in a wavy nature, with shadows being a key theme. While some waves are quite turbulent, others are just flat.

All shapes in the artwork are built using the same core logic applied in different ways. The method used to draw the waves is also used to draw the shadows, as well as the subtle textures on the surface of the waves. This homogeneous approach ensures a consistent and flowy feel to the final output.

StairWaves is coded entirely in p5.js. 

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: Fabrics #21
metadata.description:
Fabric. A collection of swatches. 

This is a project of stacked PNGs producing fabric swatches. Some are almost plaids, others are more batik, while others are more of a "magic eye" or optical illusion look. 

The PNGs were generated using VBA and conditional formatting in MS Excel, then copy/pasted as an image into MS PowerPoint, and occasionally further manipulated in different image editors including MS Paint. Images were batch resized to match each other at 1125x1125.

There are a lot of options for this collection. The layers and total number of options per (included "none" layers):
- Base
    - 42
- Flecking 
    - 18
- Broad
    - 50
- Underpin
    - 43
- Warp
    - 21
- Weft
    - 26
- Overpins
    - 43
- Mask
    - 21
- Texture
    - 14


There is a slight potential to mint the "imaginary fabric", one which is comprised of only "none" layers. That is the best of the bunch, because it is only limited by your imagination. Consider it the legendary.

There should be an interplay between the coded elements of each individual PNG and the overall stack. The randomness of coded layers stacked with other, dissimilar (base) coded layers generates interesting, and at times, colorful patterns that don't have a singular, obvious, overarching algo.

Hope you enjoy! 

Stacking achieved using PureSpider's pfp code https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

License CC BY-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Textile Bacteria #72
metadata.description:
Telar's code became self-aware and tried to escape. I built a containment unit. "Textile Bacteria" is the result.

--

The piece is based on the 1970's work of the British mathematician John Conway's "Conway's Game of Life" cellular automaton. To avoid bacteria from dying when one of the threads ends up entirely on top of the other the algorithm adds one pseudorandom artificial cross in the weaving feeding the creatures keeping at the same time the weave consistent.

- Left-click to feed dead bacteria.
- Use the arrow keys to flip between the face and the back of the fabric.
- Press 'SPACE' on your keyboard to pause/play. 
- Press 'ENTER' on your keyboard to rewind. 
- Press 'F' on your keyboard to toggle between full-screen and regular view. 
- Press 'S' on your keyboard to save it as a 36 megapixels print.
